  "prompt": "What is Precision-Recall (PR) curve?",
  "response": "The Precision-Recall (PR) curve is a graphical representation of a classification model's performance, particularly useful for imbalanced datasets. Here's a comprehensive explanation:\n\n1. Definition:\n- A curve plotting Precision against Recall at various classification thresholds\n- Shows the trade-off between precision and recall for different threshold settings\n\n2. Components:\n- Precision: Proportion of true positive predictions among all positive predictions\n- Recall: Proportion of true positive predictions among all actual positive instances\n\n3. Formula:\n- Precision = TP / (TP + FP)\n- Recall = TP / (TP + FN)\n\n4. Key Characteristics:\n- X-axis: Recall\n- Y-axis: Precision\n- Different from ROC curve\n- More informative for imbalanced datasets\n\n5. Interpretation:\n- Higher curve indicates better model performance\n- Shows model's ability to identify positive instances accurately\n- Helpful in scenarios with unequal class distribution\n\n6. Use Cases:\n- Medical diagnosis\n- Fraud detection\n- Information retrieval\n- Anomaly detection\n\n7. Advantages:\n- Handles class imbalance effectively\n- Provides detailed performance insights\n- Visualizes model's predictive power\n\n8. Limitations:\n- Can be sensitive to minor changes\n- Computationally expensive to generate",
